About This Lab

This lab session is for enterprise voice and contact center engineers interested in learning about CCE certificates implementation in and troubleshooting.

A brief introduction to CCE certificates and tools is provided. Through this lab guide you will implement a Web secure communication between CCE components.

Importing the CA Root and Sub Certificates to Your PC

Importing the CA Root and Sub Certificates to Firefox on Windows or Mac

1.          Navigate to the Toolbar in the Firefox browser.

2.         Enter the link (https://mm-static.cxdemo.net/dcloud-root-ca.crt) in the URL field. The Downloading Certificate pop-up opens.

3.          Select Trust this CA to identify websites.

4.         Click OK. You have imported the root certificate.

5.          Next, enter the second link (https://mm-static.cxdemo.net/dcloud-sub-ca.crt) in the URL field. The Downloading Certificate pop-up opens.

6.         Select Trust this CA to identify websites.

7.          Click OK. You have imported the sub certificate.

Importing the CA Root and Sub Certificates to Internet Explorer (IE) and Chrome on Windows

NOTE: Windows Internet Explorer (IE) and Google Chrome use the same certificate store on Windows, so when you import the certificates for IE, the certificates will also be imported for Google Chrome. Therefore following instructions cover the import through IE.

1.          To import the CA Root and Sub certificates to Internet Explorer (IE) complete these steps.

NOTE: It is recommended that the CA Root and Sub certificates are imported with IE and NOT with Internet Edge for Windows 10.

2.         Enter the link (https://mm-static.cxdemo.net/dcloud-root-ca.crt) in the URL field.

3.          At the bottom of the screen a prompt opens requesting you either Open, Save, or Cancel the operation.

4.         Click Open.

5.          If you get a Security pop-up window opening and prompting you to Allow or Dont Allow, click on Allow.

6.         The Certificate pop-up window opens with the General tab displayed.

7.          Click Install Certificate.

 

8.         The Certificate Import Wizard opens. Select Local Machine.

9.         Click Next. The next Wizard pop-up opens.

10.      Select Place all certificates in the following stores.

11.      Click Browse and then the Select Certificates Store screen opens.

 

12.      In the Select Certificate Store pop-up, select Trusted Root Certificates Authorities option, and click OK.

13.      You are returned to the Certificate Import Wizard with the Certificate Store field displaying your selection.

14.      Click Next.

15.      Click Finish. A prompt opens notifying you that the import was successful.

16.      Next, enter the second link (https://mm-static.cxdemo.net/dcloud-sub-ca.crt) in the URL field.

17.       At the bottom of the screen a prompt opens requesting you either Open, Save, or Cancel the operation.

18.      Click Open.

19.      If you get a Security pop-up window opening and prompting you to Allow or Dont Allow, click on Allow. The Certificate pop-up window opens with the General tab displayed.

20.      Click Install Certificate.

21.      The Certificate Import Wizard opens. Select Local Machine.

22.      Click Next. The next Wizard pop-up opens.

 

23.      Select Place all certificates in the following stores.

24.      Click Browse and the Select Certificates Store screen opens.

25.      In the Select Certificate Store pop-up, select Trusted Root Certificates Authorities option, and click OK.

 

26.     You are returned to the Certificate Import Wizard with the Certificate Store field displaying your selection.

27.      Click Next.

28.      Click Finish. A prompt opens notifying you that the import was successful.

29.     You have successfully imported the required CA certificates.

 

Importing the CA Root and Sub Certificates to Safari and Chrome on Mac

NOTE: Safari and Google Chrome use the same certificate store on Mac, so when you import the certificates for Safari, the certificates will also be imported for Google Chrome. Therefore following instructions cover the import through Safari.

To import the CA Root and Sub certificates to Safari complete these steps.

1.          Enter the link (https://mm-static.cxdemo.net/dcloud-root-ca.crt) in the URL field.

2.         The file dcloud-root-ca.crt is downloaded.

3.          Go to Finder and double click on the downloaded certificate file.

4.         The Keychain Access tool automatically opens.

5.          The Add Certificates pop-up window asks if you want to add the certificate in the keychain. Keep the default Keychain value to login and click Add.

6.         In the Keychain Access tool Search field, enter dcloud and press Enter.

7.          Look for the DCLOUDROOT-CA certificate and double click to open it.

8.         The DCLOUDROOT-CA screen opens.

9.         Click on Trust to expand the section.

10.      In the Secure Sockets Layer (SSL) drop-down, select Always Trust.

11.      Close the DCLOUDROOT-CA window and enter your MAC Password in the pop-up window. Then click Update Settings.

12.      Confirm that the certificate was trusted by searching again for dcloud. The certificate icon should change to the one shown here.

13.      Next, enter the second link (https://mm-static.cxdemo.net/dcloud-sub-ca.crt) in the URL field.

14.      The file dcloud-sub-ca.crt is downloaded.

15.      Go to Finder and double click on the downloaded certificate file.

16.      The Keychain Access tool automatically opens.

17.       The Add Certificates pop-up window asks if you want to add the certificate in the keychain. Keep the default Keychain value to login and click Add.

18.      In the Keychain Access tool Search field, enter dcloud and press Enter.

19.      Look for the DCLOUDSUB-CA certificate and double click to open it. The DCLOUDSUB-CA screen opens.

20.      Click on Trust to expand the section.

21.      In the Secure Sockets Layer (SSL) drop-down, select Always Trust.

22.      Close the DCLOUDSUB-CA window and enter your MAC Password in the pop-up window. Then click Update Settings.

23.      Confirm that the certificate was trusted by searching again for dcloud. The certificate icon should change to the one shown here.

24.      You have successfully imported the required CA certificates.

 

Creating a dCloud Customer Profile

NOTE: In case you dont get prompted with your name but rather with Michael Littlefoot, you need to create your customer profile. We have created our own dCloud users database, which is part of the dCloud Collaboration Toolbox used for Contact Center Instant demos. You will need to register on our dCloud Collaboration Toolbox, if youre not already registered, and create your Customer Profile.

 

1.    Log into dCloud and search for the Cisco Unified Contact Center Express 12.0v2 demo in the dCloud catalog.

2.    Click on Related Documents then Customer Profiles Toolbox.

3.    The dCloud Collaboration Toolbox screen opens and shows a login form.

4.    If first time user, click Create Account link under the login form.

5.    The Create Your dCloud Toolbox Account screen opens.

6.    Fill in the following information:

a.          First Name

b.         Last Name

c.          Cisco CCO email address for dCloud

d.         Username (your choice, must be unique in our system)

e.         4-digit user ID (your choice, must be unique in our system)

f.           New Password (NOT your Cisco Password)

g.         Password confirmation

7.    Click Customer Profiles.

8.    Click on the Add Customer button.

9.    Enter your customer information. You need to enter at least First Name and Last Name.

10.  Enter any phone number or email address that you will use for the demo. Click Add Phone/Email button after each entry.

NOTE: Please follow the directions below for the phone number, otherwise you will not be recognized when calling the demo.

- If you are in the US and are calling a session in the US, enter your 10-digit phone number.

- If you are in the UK and your session is in the UK, enter your phone number without the leading zero.

- If you are in Singapore and your session is in Singapore, enter your 8-digit phone number.

- If you are calling a session abroad your country, enter your number with the country code (no leading zero).

11.  Once done click on the Save New Customer button.

 

Certificates Overview

Certificates are used to ensure that communication is secure by authenticating clients and servers.

In the Package Contact Center Enterprise (PCCE) solution version 12.x all components of the solution are controlled by Single Pane of Glass (SPOG), which is hosted in the principal Admin Workstation (AW) server.

 

Due to Security Management Compliance (SRC) in the PCCE 12.5(1) version, all communication between SPOG and other components in the solution are done via secure HTTP protocol.

Cisco Unified Contact Center Certificate Implementation

Users can purchase certificates from a Certificate Authority (CA signed certificates) or they can use self-signed certificates.

Self-Signed Certificates

Self-signed certificates (as the name implies) are signed and issued by the same entity who certifies it. These certificates are signed with ones own private key. Trust becomes questionable. Exceptions must be granted by each relying trust.

Avoid using self-signed certificates for any sensitive, public communications.

CA Signed Certificates

Certificates from a Certificate Authority (CA) certifies the public key certificate ownership of the named subject or entity through a certificate chain of trust. CAs act as trusted third-party entities and validates that the public key corresponds with the owners private key. Trust is implicit.

Are self-signed certificates less secure? No! Advantages of third-party (CA) certificates are ease of use (universal, it just works), implicit trust, and avoids extra work to deploy on every endpoint device (servers and workstations).

Trace Collection

Exercise 1.

Step 1. Remote login to Rogger/PG/AWHDS and login to Diagnostic framework portico and click SetTraceLevel

Step 2. Select a component and choose desired Level.

Step 3. To check the current trace level, Click GetTraceLevel in the left side and Choose a Component and Submit.

 

Exercise 2. Collect logs

Step 1. Click ListTraceFiles and select a component.

Step 2. Key in From and To date and Time and click Submit.

Step 3. Click the zip file to download the logs.

Exercise 5. Dumplog

Step 1. Remote log to Rogger/PG/AWHDS. Open command prompt.

Step 2. Change directory to log available path as cdlog <instane name> <Service name>

Command to collect multiple logs: dumplog <services separated by space> /last /of <log file name>.txt

Step 3. You can open the file either by type <log file name>.txt or go the change directory path and open the file.

Exercise 7. Finesse logs

Step 1. Login to Finesse cli via putty.

Step 2. <ip address>, username: Administrator password: C1sco12345

Step 3. To check the current Finesse trace status, utils finesse trace status

Step 4. To enable utils finesse trace enable

 

 

 

admin:utils finesse trace status

Trace logging is disabled.

admin:utils finesse trace enable

Warning: Enabling trace logging may cause an overload in the system. This has to be used strictly for debugging purposes only.

Warning: Command dispatcher logs will also be enabled.

Press ENTER to continue. Press any other key to exit :

Trace logging has been enabled. The settings will take effect within a minute.

admin:utils finesse trace status

Some trace levels are enabled in the system. Run the disable command to turn everything off; Run the enable command to turn everything on.
 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 


Step 5. To collect the logs via browser, url: <ipaddress>/finesse/logs. Click any logs from list and download the logs.

Step 6. To collect the logs via cli

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

admin:file get activelog desktop ?

Syntax:

file get activelog file-spec [options]

file-spec mandatory file to transfer

options optional reltime months|weeks|days|hours|minutes timevalue

abstime hh:mm:MM/DD/YY hh:mm:MM/DD/YY

match regex

recurs

compress

admin:file get activelog desktop reltime hours 1 compress

admin:file get activelog desktop abstime 14:30:10/05/20 14:45:10/05/20 compress

Exercise 8. Cisco VOS Platform CLI commands

To collect details of Cisco VOS platforms such as CUIC, Live data, CUCM, Finesse etc..

Login to cli of the server via putty,and execute the commands and gather output.

admin:show network eth0 detail

admin: show network cluster

admin: show version active

admin: show status

admin: show process load cpu**

admin: show process load memory**

admin: utils dbreplication runtimestate

admin: utils diagnose test
 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 


Logging in to the Diagnostic Framework Portico

Step 1. In Rogger, PG, AWHDS, Diagnostic Framework Portico can be opened either via Unified CCE Tools or from Desktop shortcut.

 

Step 2. Double click on the Diagnostic framework portico shortcut

Step 3. Click Advanced button and Accept the risk on the certiticate prompt if any

Step 4. Enter the domain admin/user credentials and click Sign in

Step 5. The webpage redirects to the Diagnostic framework portico home page

 

Excersice 1 Router Interfaces: Central Controller Agent CCAG

 

Step 1. Login to the Rogger A server Diagnostic Portico, Click on the Listprocesses under the Service Menu


Step 2. The installed services and processes will be listed in the page with status

 

Step 3. Check the Router A service status

 

 

 

Step 4. Take a look at the CC Agent process in the Router Service

a)    Under the Router service ccagent.exe process listed

b)    CC Agent process status as InSvc (In Service)

c)    Number of configured PG in the Router is 3 and connected pg

d)    Process Uptime in the format Days.Hours:Mins:Secs which resets at service restart

 

Step 5. Open the registry in the Rogger and take look at the below KeyNames

HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\SOFTWARE\Cisco Systems, Inc.\ICM\pcce\RouterA\DMP\CurrentVersion\CCLocalSide\LowPriority\Port

 

HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\SOFTWARE\Cisco Systems, Inc.\ICM\pcce\RouterA\DMP\CurrentVersion\CCLocalSide\MediumPriority\Port

HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\SOFTWARE\Cisco Systems, Inc.\ICM\pcce\RouterA\DMP\CurrentVersion\CCLocalSide\HighPriority\Port

 

Step 2. Open the command prompt

 

 

Step 3. Access the RTTest utility by entering the commands rttest /cust Customer /node ICRNode

Step 4. Enter the command status in the rttest utility

Step 5. Look at the Logical controller list, status, uptime, last heartbeat

C PG downloaded config from Router

F fully configured, config is valid

O PG is online

 

Step 6. Enter the command status /offline in the rttest utility

 

Step 7. Enter the command status /full in the rttest utility (This incl offline PGs and PIMs offline)

Exercise 2 Router Interfaces: DB Agent DBAG

Step 1. Login to the Rogger A server Diagnostic Portico, Click on the Listprocesses under the Service Menu

Step 2. Look at the DB Agent process

a)    Under the Router service dbagent.exe process listed

b)    Process uptime in the Days.Hours:Mins:Secs format

c)    Perform a simple configuration change from CCE Admin, CFG MGR or Script Editor

d)    Use the dumplog utility to collect the DBA process logs

e)    Sequence of message for configuration changes in the DBA logs

f)     Connect to the Logger database using SQL studio and perform the below query against the SideA DB

g)    Use the dumpcfg utility and reterieve the Config Message information

 

Exercise 3 - Router Interfaces: Real-Time Server RTS

Step 1. Login to the Rogger A server Diagnostic Portico, Click on the Listprocesses under the Service Menu

Step 2. Look at the RealTime Server process

a)    Under the Router service rtsvr.exe process listed

b)    Process uptime in the Days.Hours:Mins:Secs format

c)    Open the registry settings and review the port number

HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\SOFTWARE\Cisco Systems, Inc.\ICM\ucce\RouterA\RealTimeServer\CurrentVersion\ RTServerLocalIPPortNo

d)    Open the command prompt and enter the netstat command

 

e)    Use the dumplog utility and collect the Realtime Server logs

f)     Enable the debug level trace for the Realtime server

g)    Login to the AW-HDS server and enable the debug level trace for the Realtime distributor (AW-HDS) and perform a simple change

h)    Use the dumplog utility and collect the realtime server logs

i)     Go to the AW-HDS server and use the dumplog utility to collect the realtime distributor logs

 

 

Exercise 3 Router Inter Process Communication MDS

 

Step 1. Login to the Rogger A server Diagnostic Portico, Click on the Listprocesses under the Service Menu

Step 2. Look at the MDS process

a)    Under the Router service mds.exe process listed

b)    Process uptime in the Days.Hours:Mins:Secs format

c)    MDS process status as InSvc

d)    Since this is a simplex deployment the MDS is in isolated mode and acts as Enabled Syncronizer

 

Exercise 4 Peripheral Gateway Interfaces PGAG

Step 1. Login to the PG A server Diagnostic Portico, Click on the Listprocesses under the Service Menu

 

Step 2. Look at the PG Agent process stats

a)    Process status is in Service and states the Side A is Active

b)    Process uptime status as Days.Hours:Mins:Secs

c)    Open the command prompt and execute netstat command to see the PG-RTR connections

Low, Medium and High priority Active and Idle connections to both Central Controllers. (only active connections available for simplex deployment)

 

d)    Open the command prompt and execute the opctest utility

 

e)    Enter the command status and look at the PG Agent status

Simplex

Duplex

f)     Check the periphrels status in the diagnostic framework portico

 

 

g)    Check the peripherals status in the OPCTest utility

h)    Open the command prompt and execute netstat status to see the Live Data connection

i)     Check the status of the MDS in the diagnostic framework portico

a)    MDS service status is In Service

b)    Isolated Mode

c)    Enabled syncronizer

j)     Open the task manager and see each PG runs a dedicated MDS process

k)    Open the registry setting and review the MDS port configuration

HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\SOFTWARE\Cisco Systems, Inc.\ICM\ucce\PG3A\MDS\CurrentVersion\DedicatedPath\HighPriority\Port

HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\SOFTWARE\Cisco Systems, Inc.\ICM\ucce\PG3A\MDS\CurrentVersion\DedicatedPath\MediumPriority\Port

HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\SOFTWARE\Cisco Systems, Inc.\ICM\ucce\PG3A\MDS\CurrentVersion\DedicatedPath\LowPriority\Port

l)     Open the command prompt and execute netstat command to see MDS connection status

Step 1. Login to the PG A server Diagnostic Portico, Click on the Listprocesses under the Service Menu

Exercise 6 T_Event table

 

1.    Login to the Logger server and connect to the database using SQL studio

2.    Execute the below query and retrieve the list of table entries

Select CentralControllerFileTime, Severity, ProcName, Categoty, MessageString from the t_event where CentralControllerFileTime > 2020-10-20 00:00

3.    Review the list alarms logged in the table

 

Exercise 7 Performance Counter

 

1.    Login to the Rogger / AW / PG server and launch the performance monitor tool in the CCE Tools folder

2.    Navigate to the Folder Perform under the C:\icm\serviceability and locate CCE.xml

3.    Add the performance counter and add the cce.xml file as user defined

4.    Performance counters are stored in the desired location

5.    Open the file and review the performance counter information for the various components

6.    Navigate to Diagnostic portico and use the GetAlarm link retrieve the list of alarms
